We will utilize the reward-to-risk ratio to compute the risk-free rate of the two securities, Stock Y and Z. 

The reward-to-risk ratio occurs until the securities are shown on the same line using the security market line, indicating that they offered the same payoff for taking a risk.

The reward-to-risk ratio is shown as follows: 

$$\begin{aligned}
\dfrac{\text{R }_\text{Stock Y}{- }{R}_{f}}{\text{B}_\text{Stock Y}}&=\dfrac{\text{R }_\text{Stock Z}{- }{R}_{f}}{\text{B}_\text{Stock Z}}
\end{aligned}$$
Where: 
$$\begin{aligned}
{\text{R}_{}}& = {\text{Expected return}} \\
{\text{R}_{f}}& = {\text{Risk-free interest rate }} \\

{\text{B}}&= {\text{Beta}} 
\end{aligned}$$

Now, let us divide both sides by 0.40\%. This is to cancel out the coefficient of the risk-free rate. This is computed as follows:

$$\begin{aligned}

\dfrac{\text{0.40R}_{f}}{\text{0.40}}&=\dfrac{\text{0.54\%  }}{\text{0.40}}\\
&={\textbf{1.35\%}}
\end{aligned}$$
